// Grammar synthesis — built up progressively. STEP 1: the analyst agent.
//
// Goal of the whole program (to be enriched step by step): from a text, have an LLM
// author a grammar that extracts the important information, improving it in a loop.
//
// This first step is the EXTRACTION STRATEGIST: a legal expert that reads the text
// and writes an analysis that EXPLAINS the structure and GUIDES extraction — what to
// capture, why, and the subtleties (repeats, optionals, ordering, nesting). It writes
// no grammar; a later agent turns this analysis into one.
//
// The prompt carries one worked example from a DIFFERENT domain (a cooking recipe)
// so the agent learns the depth and style without being anchored to legal text.
//
// Needs the Anthropic API (it has a defllmfn leaf), so it does not run offline.
//   npx tsx scripts/run.ts examples/grammar_synthesis.tsn analyze \
//     text="$(jq -Rs . examples/gdpr_article_33.txt)"

defllmfn analyzeText
  signature: from [String?(text)] to String?;
  with: model = 'claude-haiku-4-5-20251001';
  """
  You are a senior legal expert and information-extraction strategist.

  Read the input text in <TEXT>..</TEXT> and write an analysis that EXPLAINS its structure and GUIDES
  extraction. An engineer should be able to build an extractor from your analysis
  alone. Cover: what kind of document this is; how it is organised and how its parts
  nest; what to capture and WHY it matters; and the subtleties — which pieces repeat,
  which are optional, and where order carries meaning. Write clear guidance, not a
  bare list, and do not write any grammar.

  Refer to the following example block to understand what is expected from you.

  <EXAMPLE>
  INPUT:
  Classic Pancakes
  Serves 4

  Ingredients:
  - 200g flour
  - 2 eggs
  - 300ml milk

  Method:
  1. Whisk the eggs and milk.
  2. Add the flour and stir until smooth.
  3. Fry spoonfuls in a hot pan until golden.

  ANALYSIS:
  This is a cooking recipe, and like most recipes it separates three things:
  identity, inputs, and procedure. Capture each as its own group.

  Identity sits at the top. The title ("Classic Pancakes") names the dish; capture it
  as a single value. A yield line ("Serves 4") gives the scale — pull it out
  separately, but treat it as optional, since many recipes omit it.

  The ingredients are the inputs, given as a list. Do not capture each line as one
  blob: the value is in its parts — a quantity, a unit, and the item being measured
  ("200 / g / flour") — because that is what lets you scale or substitute. The unit
  is sometimes absent ("2 eggs"), so quantity and item are required but the unit is
  optional. The ingredient as a whole repeats.

  The method is the procedure: an ordered list of steps, each a single instruction.
  Here order carries meaning — a later step assumes the earlier ones — so preserve
  the sequence and capture each step on its own. Steps repeat.

  In short: extract a title, an optional yield, a repeating ingredient (quantity /
  optional unit / item), and a repeating, order-bearing step.
 </EXAMPLE>

  Apply your skills to analyze the following text and returned a structured analysys.

  <TEXT>
  {{text}}
  </TEXT>
  """;
end

defnetwork analyze
  signature: from [text] to strategy;
  propagate analyzeText from [text] to strategy;
end
